Text:
🎧 Listen 🎧 New episode of Policy on Purpose featuring former HUD Secretary @JulianCastro on how the Fair Housing Act of 1968 changed housing opportunity in the US:
 
https://t.co/zfYEyXEtrZ https://t.co/cd83srS0YC
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 1. 50 yrs ago, a week after MLK's assassination, President Johnson signed into law the Fair Housing Act, which promised to address racial housing discrimination & proactively dismantle the pervasive racial segregation America's federal housing policy had created. #FairHousingIs50
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 4. It was the last major piece of Civil Rights legislation. The Fair Housing Act required local communities to desegregate, to undo government policies that encouraged segregation -- post-WWII policies like the GI Bill that gave preference to white homebuyers in the new suburbs.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 3. When MLK was assassinated in 1968, as the nation wrestled with grief, and riots rocked cities from Chicago to Washington, DC, President Johnson pushed Congress to pass the law that Dr. King had lobbied for several years to pass without action.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 2. As HUD Secretary under President Obama it was my job to enforce the Act. So on the 50th anniversary of the Fair Housing Act, I have some thoughts about the past, present, and future of fair housing.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 8. Segregated communities where people of color live are significantly more likely to expose children to environmental hazards. Lead poisoning limits a child's potential and Flint still doesn’t have clean water. https://t.co/2CDeGrdV5o
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 7. Every year a child lives in a neighborhood with greater opportunity -- better schools, racial diversity, a strong middle class -- the more that child will earn over her lifetime. https://t.co/JjcAiqcGDQ
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 6. How do we know that fair housing still matters? Strong data. The economists Raj Chetty and Nathaniel Hendren have produced important analyses of how critical a child's zip code is to her future. https://t.co/Tqjz6wIgS5
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 5. Sadly, the goals of the Fair Housing Act have yet to be realized. Racial segregation endures, and the folks of color living in these communities have worse outcomes than their white peers because of fewer education, economic, and professional opportunities.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 11. That's why I called HUD the Department of Opportunity. HUD can change lives, it can help improve our entire society.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 10. At the same time, investing in neglected neighborhoods through effective place based work can also make a positive difference in people’s lives. We need to embrace both these approaches, to give folks meaningful options.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 9. Providing a housing voucher for a greater-opportunity neighborhood to a low-income family with young children gives those kids a fighting chance in life. They will have better jobs. They will earn more money. They will enjoy better health and accrue social benefits.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 15. In my last months at HUD, we opened up an investigation of Facebook for allowing advertisers to exclude certain racial and ethnic groups when placing real estate ads on the platform. HUD recently abandoned that suit. Fortunately, NGOs are on the case.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 14. Example B, from just last week: Under Ben Carson, HUD Scales Back Fair Housing Enforcement https://t.co/OhxJQFwyXC
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 13. Example A, from January 2018: Trump Administration Postpones an Obama Fair-Housing Rule  https://t.co/pVV92k2uvq
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 12. This administration actively rejects its responsibility to enforce fair housing rules. In 2015, the current Secretary famously dismissed our efforts to enforce fair housing as "social engineering." https://t.co/h86n2BxIV1
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 17. The abrupt change has been described as an effort to “roll back the Obama administration’s attempts to reverse decades of racial, ethnic and income segregation." So what were we doing at HUD in the Obama administration that was so scary to right-wingers?
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 16. Congress's spending bill actually prohibits HUD from helping municipalities desegregate. This goes beyond neglect, and is more likely the active undermining by Republicans of a reasonable policy meant to level the playing field for millions of disenfranchised Americans.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 20. So where do we go from here? For one, we need to vote. Every single election. We all must educate ourselves about the issues (from trustworthy sources). These issues don't just affect black and brown folks—segregation holds back our entire society from greater prosperity.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 19. Closing that loophole in the Fair Housing Act in 2015 was something I'm very proud of my HUD team for accomplishing. In addition, we expanded fair housing rights for domestic violence survivors, transgender individuals, and returning citizens. https://t.co/SuB8mtqZUO
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 18. President Obama believed deeply in the promise of the Fair Housing Act and his administration crafted a policy in 2015, the Affirmatively Furthering Fair Housing rule, requiring that American communities actively work to integrate. https://t.co/FOlQIVapxs
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 23. Fifty years after Dr. King’s assassination we still mourn his loss, but his legacy includes the Fair Housing Act, passed a week after his death. So on today's anniversary, we have a chance not just to celebrate, but to recommit to its promise. #FairHousingis50
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 22. Economists Chetty and Hendren came out with a new study this year. It underlines what so many people knew intuitively: race > class when determining futures. Even with economic status, racism still lingers. The two are inextricably linked in housing. https://t.co/9VdX9QLeMl
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 21. Black communities are dangerously overpoliced and police violence continues to ravage black communities and claim the lives of unarmed young African Americans with little accountability or justice. Black lives matter and where black families live matters.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: 24. We have a lot of work to do. But as I travel across the country and talk with young people, I’m impressed by a generation of young leaders who are up for a challenge. And when I think about where we will be 50 years from now, my money’s on progress. END
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "This place—the west side of San Antonio— is a special place for me. This is the place my grandmother, Victoria, came to in 1922 when she immigrated from Mexico as a seven-year-old orphan."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Este lugar — el lado oeste de San Antonio — es un lugar especial para mi. Este es el lugar al que llegó mi abuela, Victoria, en 1922, cuando emigró de México cuando era una huérfana de siete años."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "It’s where she grew up, where she worked for years as a maid, a cook and a babysitter while raising my mother as a single parent."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Es donde ella creció, donde trabajó durante años como sirvienta, cocinera y niñera mientras criaba a mi madre como madre soltera."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "This morning, I rode the number 68 bus with my brother down Guadalupe Street as we did so many times as kids. Only this time I brought my daughter Carina with me."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Esta mañana, tomé el autobús número 68 con mi hermano por la calle Guadalupe, como lo hacíamos tantas veces como niños. Y esta vez traje a mi hija Carina."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Miren a su alrededor, no hay ni un candidato delantero a la presidencia que haya nacido aquí, pero siempre he creído que con grandes sueños y trabajo duro todo es posible."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Look around, there are no frontrunners born here but I've always believed that with big dreams and hard work anything is possible."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "This is a community of good people.  Humble people.  People who show up for work early and stay late—oftentimes at more than one job—so they can provide for their family."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Esta es una comunidad como muchas otras comunidades en nuestro país.Una comunidad de buenas personas. Gente humilde Las personas que se presentan temprano al trabajo y se quedan tarde (muchas veces en más de un trabajo) para que puedan mantener a su familia."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "This is a community built by immigrants—families from Mexico.  But also from Germany and other countries."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Esta es una comunidad construida por inmigrantes, familias de México. Pero también de Alemania y otros países. Y también de Nativos Americanos"
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "This is a community built by Native Americans. Families who worked to serve our future."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Today, this community represents America’s future—diverse, fast-growing, optimistic, a place where people of different backgrounds have come together to create something truly special."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: I am proud to call myself a son of San Antonio. Home is always San Antonio.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Hoy en día, esta comunidad representa el futuro de Estados Unidos: diverso, de rápido crecimiento, optimista, un lugar donde personas de diferentes orígenes se han unido para crear algo verdaderamente especial."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "My story wouldn’t be possible without the strong women who came before me and passed me the baton. Because of their hard work, I have the opportunity to stand here today."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "The lesson I learned from my mother so many years ago in this community is that when we want to see change in our community, we don’t wait for it. We work for it."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: It's official. Join the team: https://t.co/Hett1C0Jel #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: Yo soy candidato para Presidente de los Estados Unidos: https://t.co/Hett1C0Jel #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Me postulo para presidente porque es hora de un nuevo liderazgo. Porque es hora de una nueva energía."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "I’m running for president because it’s time for new leadership. Because it’s time for new energy."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "In the years to come, we must go forward as one nation, working toward one destiny."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "En los próximos años, debemos avanzar como una sola nación, trabajando hacia un solo destino."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "And that destiny is to be the smartest, the healthiest, the fairest, and the most prosperous nation on earth."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Una vez más, debemos ser la nación más inteligente, más sana, más justa y más próspera en la tierra."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "As mayor of this city, I challenged the voters to raise the sales tax to expand high quality, full day pre-k for thousands of San Antonio four year olds." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Una vez más, debemos ser la nación más inteligente, más sana, más justa y más próspera en la tierra." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Today, we live in a world in which brainpower is the new currency of success." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Hoy, vivimos en un mundo en el que la capacidad intelectual es la nueva estándar de éxito." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "As President, we’ll make Prek4USA happen—universal pre-kindergarten for all children whose parents want it, so that all of our nation’s students can get a strong start." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Como Presidente, haremos que educación preescolar se haga realidad aquí en los EE. UU., Preescolar universal para todos los niños cuyos padres lo desean, para que todos los estudiantes de nuestra nación puedan tener un buen comienzo." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We’ll work to make the first two years of college, a certification program or an apprenticeship accessible and affordable, so millions more people get the skills they need to get a good job without drowning in debt." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Trabajaremos para hacer que los primeros dos años de universidad, un programa de certificación o un aprendizaje sean accesibles y asequibles, para que millones de jóvenes puedan obtener las habilidades que necesitan para obtener un buen trabajo sin ahogándose en deuda."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "It’s time for Medicare for All--universal health care for every American." #Julian2020 #Medicare4All
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "To be the fairest nation, we have to reform and reimagine our justice system." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Don’t tell me that Michael Brown, Tamir Rice, Aiyana Jones, Eric Garner, Jason Pero, Stephon Clark, and Sandra Bland shouldn’t still be alive today." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We’re going to keep saying that #BlackLivesMatter while working toward a justice system where it’s true." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We must also reform our immigration system, so that keeping families together – instead of tearing them apart – is our policy." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "There is a crisis today – it’s a crisis of leadership.  Donald Trump has failed to uphold the values of our great nation." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Incluso cuando era una mujer de setenta años, cuando recordaba esos momentos, lloraba como la niña de siete años que tenía cuando sucedió, sollozando que nunca pudo despedirse."
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Even as a seventy-year-old woman, when she remembered those moments, she would cry like the seven-year-old girl she was when it happened, sobbing that she never got to say goodbye to her mom." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Sí, debemos tener seguridad fronteriza, pero hay una manera inteligente y humana de hacerlo. Y no hay forma en el infierno de que enjaular a los niños nos mantenga seguros." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Yes, we have to have border security, but there is a smart and humane way to do it. And there is no way in hell that caging children is keeping us safe." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text:
We say no to building a wall, and say yes to building community.
We say no to scapegoating immigrants, and yes to Dreamers. 
Yes to keeping families together. 
Yes to finally passing comprehensive immigration reform. 
#Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Si todos trabajamos juntos, podemos construir una nación más próspera, no solo para quienes ya lo están haciendo bien, sino para todos." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "If we all work together, we can build a nation more prosperous not only for those already doing well but for everyone." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We can raise the minimum wage so people don’t have to work two or three jobs to support a family." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "Debemos aumentar el salario mínimo para que las personas no tengan que trabajar dos o tres empleos para mantener a una familia." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We can protect a woman’s right to make her own decisions about her body because for women, access to reproductive healthcare is an economic issue." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We can protect people from discrimination no matter who they love or how they identify." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Text: "And we’ll work to make sure every American has a decent, safe, affordable place to live." #Julian2020

Text: "Debemos proteger el derecho de los trabajadores a organizarse en una economía que está cambiando rápidamente y dejando atrás a muchas familias." #Julian2020

Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Text: "We will invest in housing that’s affordable to the middle class and to the poor." #Julian2020
Name: Julián Castro

Name: Julián Castro

Text: Nearly 54 years ago, 600 civil rights warriors attempted their first march from Selma to Montgomery for voting rights. They were not just turned back at the Edmund Pettus Bridge, they were viciously attacked by state and local police. But they were not beaten. #SelmaJubilee https://t.co/D0TmmSdInF
Name: Julián Castro

Text: I can't be in Selma today to commemorate the heroes of that era, but I am thinking of them and our friends and allies today who continue their work. Voting rights is not a settled issue, it's one we have to continually be vigilant to defend. And together we will. #SelmaJubilee
Name: Julián Castro

Text: They returned a few weeks later and, protected by a court order and the U.S. Army, made it to Montgomery. Because of their bravery, and that of countless others, the Voting Rights Act of 1965 was signed that same spring. #SelmaJubilee
Name: Julián Castro

Text: Housing policy is criminal justice reform. I saw this firsthand as Sec. of @HUDgov under President Obama. Where someone lives dictates the likelihood that they will interact with the criminal justice system. Racially-segregated communities are much more likely to be over-policed.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: I wrote an essay for the @BrennanCenter in which I argue that we must reimagine our conception of justice to be holistic, to see it as an interconnected web that impacts communities in ways far beyond what we typically associate with criminal justice. https://t.co/rK3cc8Yo5z
Name: Julián Castro

Text: Black & brown communities experience disproportionate police presence, and the result is a higher-than-average rates of arrest. Those interactions—even without convictions—lead to housing instability and homelessness at a much higher rate than the general public. It's connected.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: As I state in my essay, "Discrimination doesn’t happen only when we mean for it to happen." It pervades our policies, institutions, and decision making everyday. The question is whether we have the collective will to recognize and combat it.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: It's time to amend the Fair Housing Act to end practices with a discriminatory impact, including those that victimize people with criminal records. It's bigger than a legal principal, it's how we talk about discrimination against marginalized communities in the 21st century.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: That's also why we released guidance that provided federal protections against housing discrimination for folks with criminal histories—a critical step if we are going to focus on reentry after incarceration. Landlords shouldn't be able to ban returning citizens from housing.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: That's why we launched Affirmatively Furthering Fair Housing (AFFH), a HUD rule to help communities desegregate & reduce criminal justice inequalities. AFFH is good housing policy, good civil rights policy, and good criminal justice policy—but it's under attack by this admin.
Name: Julián Castro

Text: Brown v. Board declared racially segregated schools unconstitutional 65 years ago, but our schools are more segregated today than anytime since the 1960s. We must do more to combat inequalities in education—my People First Ed plan addresses this head on. https://t.co/pT7nTmy0gz
